488
00:26:11,750 --> 00:26:13,450
I didn't say that right, did I?

489
00:26:13,460 --> 00:26:15,060
Sure you did.

490
00:26:17,110 --> 00:26:19,750
- I'll be around, Nora.   
- I hope so.

491
00:26:31,480 --> 00:26:33,170
Hey, you're back.

492
00:26:33,680 --> 00:26:35,910
So, uh, where'd you put the letter?

493
00:26:36,340 --> 00:26:37,520
What letter?

494
00:26:37,530 --> 00:26:38,970
The form letter.

495
00:26:38,980 --> 00:26:41,430
You know, the one you were trying to get Kitty to get me to sign.

496
00:26:41,820 --> 00:26:44,060
Yeah, you're busted, Mom. She told me.

497
00:26:44,070 --> 00:26:45,480
I'm sorry, Justin.

498
00:26:45,490 --> 00:26:48,300
Look, it's cool. I just want to see it, that's all.

499
00:26:48,720 --> 00:26:50,750
Been doing some rethinking.

500
00:26:50,760 --> 00:26:53,660
That's great. I threw it out.

501
00:26:53,670 --> 00:26:57,240
Kitty told me you wouldn't be interested, so I went and threw it out.

502
00:27:07,220 --> 00:27:09,530
You sent it in already.

503
00:27:13,970 --> 00:27:16,500
I knew you would eventually change your mind.

504
00:27:20,240 --> 00:27:21,770
What are you doing?

505
00:27:21,780 --> 00:27:24,590
I'm gonna call the recruiter and tell him to ignore that letter.

506
00:27:24,600 --> 00:27:27,040
- Justin...     
- I shoulda done this a long time ago.

507
00:27:27,050 --> 00:27:28,510
I mean, Kitty knew. She knew that was the only way

508
00:27:28,520 --> 00:27:30,820
she was gonna have a life was to get as far away from you as possible.

509
00:27:30,830 --> 00:27:34,600
I want you to have a life.  That's the whole point. Please.

510
00:27:34,610 --> 00:27:37,700
I don't want you to do something I know you will regret!

511
00:27:37,710 --> 00:27:39,240
That's right. You know, right?

512
00:27:39,250 --> 00:27:41,820
You know what I should do and how I should do it, Mom.

513
00:27:42,230 --> 00:27:45,230
Because you're my whole life.

514
00:27:46,240 --> 00:27:49,770
No, Mom, I'm your son. I've got my own life.

515
00:28:00,410 --> 00:28:02,050
Where'd you learn to break like that?

516
00:28:02,060 --> 00:28:04,210
Three brothers and a dad.

517
00:28:04,220 --> 00:28:06,380
Uh, are you done having...

518
00:28:06,560 --> 00:28:08,280
Fun yet?

519
00:28:09,890 --> 00:28:11,510
I love this song.

520
00:28:20,110 --> 00:28:23,060
- Dance, Tommy.  
- Couldn't you just kill me instead?

521
00:28:33,270 --> 00:28:34,720
Your sister has how many kids?

522
00:28:34,730 --> 00:28:37,120
I honestly don't know anymore.

523
00:28:37,710 --> 00:28:38,490
How about you?

524
00:28:38,500 --> 00:28:39,860
No, I-I don't have any kids.

525
00:28:39,870 --> 00:28:42,610
And I don't envision that happening anytime soon

526
00:28:42,620 --> 00:28:44,570
'cause for one thing, I'm gay.

527
00:28:44,580 --> 00:28:48,290
So an unplanned pregnancy isn't really a risk for me.

528
00:28:48,300 --> 00:28:51,090
For another, you kinda need to be in a long-term relationship,

529
00:28:51,100 --> 00:28:54,990
and my--my boyfriend just broke up with me so...

530
00:28:55,000 --> 00:28:57,010
So you're single.

531
00:28:58,230 --> 00:29:00,190
I was hoping you'd say that.

532
00:29:05,400 --> 00:29:07,890
Good news. No, great news.

533
00:29:07,900 --> 00:29:10,640
I've got a line on a place for us to crash tonight.

534
00:29:12,510 --> 00:29:14,100
You're incredible.

535
00:29:14,110 --> 00:29:17,110
We come to an army bar, and he gets laid.

536
00:29:17,120 --> 00:29:20,280
Well, not yet, but I am working on it.

537
00:29:24,030 --> 00:29:26,980
You're either about to do something very naughty,

538
00:29:26,990 --> 00:29:29,130
or you already have.

539
00:29:29,800 --> 00:29:31,110
What gave me away?

540
00:29:31,120 --> 00:29:35,940
The night before you cheated on Mrs. Worthington's spelling test, you ate a whole pint.

541
00:29:39,000 --> 00:29:42,680
You remember every bad thing I've ever done, don't you?

542
00:29:43,120 --> 00:29:46,300
I remember every bad thing we've both ever done.

543
00:29:48,920 --> 00:29:51,990
We, I've got a new one, one for the record books.

544
00:29:57,110 --> 00:30:00,680
I tried to bribe the senator to help Justin.

545
00:30:01,150 --> 00:30:02,730
To get him out of the military?

546
00:30:02,740 --> 00:30:08,060
Yeah, I thought that he'd be able to help Justin and get him off the hook.

547
00:30:08,750 --> 00:30:10,970
And me, too, I guess.

548
00:30:12,790 --> 00:30:15,410
It wasn't your fault that Justin enlisted.

549
00:30:15,420 --> 00:30:17,390
It was mine.

550
00:30:17,480 --> 00:30:19,840
- What are you talking about?   
- I pushed him.

551
00:30:20,430 --> 00:30:24,510
He was about to change his mind, and I pushed him the other way.

552
00:30:24,790 --> 00:30:27,100
And I blamed it on you.

553
00:30:27,510 --> 00:30:31,060
I was too angry and scared to blame it on myself.

554
00:30:31,900 --> 00:30:33,800
No. Justin would have never enlisted if I hadn't--

555
00:30:33,810 --> 00:30:36,050
You're both crazy.

556
00:30:36,330 --> 00:30:39,080
I enlisted because I wanted to.

557
00:30:40,660 --> 00:30:44,050
I went back and forth about a thousand times in my head before I went,

558
00:30:44,060 --> 00:30:48,330
and nothing anyone said or did was gonna change my mind.

559
00:30:48,340 --> 00:30:51,150
It was the best and worst decision I've made in my entire life,

560
00:30:51,160 --> 00:30:53,810
but you know what?  It was my choice.

561
00:30:55,080 --> 00:30:57,600
So I'm not going to fight the recall.

562
00:30:58,190 --> 00:31:00,020
I'm going back.

563
00:31:15,800 --> 00:31:18,020
I feel like Nick Nolte's mug shot.

564
00:31:18,310 --> 00:31:21,600
That's what happens when you do jell-o shots with enlisted men.

565
00:31:21,810 --> 00:31:23,620
If we're not as chipper as you are, Kev,

566
00:31:23,630 --> 00:31:25,300
it's because you didn't sleep on the floor.

567
00:31:25,310 --> 00:31:26,870
Oh, that's right, Tommy.

568
00:31:26,880 --> 00:31:28,740
I certainly did not.

569
00:31:31,240 --> 00:31:34,240
One day, son, this will all be yours.

570
00:31:36,980 --> 00:31:41,290
Okay, Tommy, 500 miles, two cars later, you happy now?

571
00:31:41,510 --> 00:31:42,670
Yeah, come on, Tommy, let's go.

572
00:31:42,680 --> 00:31:45,270
We've got a long trip ahead of us.

573
00:31:45,360 --> 00:31:48,390
I don't get it. How could he be this stupid?

574
00:31:48,400 --> 00:31:50,430
- No, how could you be?  
- Oh, screw you.

575
00:31:50,440 --> 00:31:53,680
- Okay, let's calm down.  
- I'm sick of her cracks about him.

576
00:31:53,690 --> 00:31:56,010
I don't care about the mistakes that he made.

577
00:31:56,020 --> 00:31:57,290
- I don't care.  
- Fine.

578
00:31:57,300 --> 00:31:58,520
All right? He was our dad.

579
00:31:58,530 --> 00:31:59,910
Not just ours.

580
00:31:59,920 --> 00:32:01,930
Excuse me?

581
00:32:01,950 --> 00:32:04,080
What--what ex-exactly does that mean?

582 
00:32:04,090 --> 00:32:06,850
You just said, "not just ours"?  What...

583
00:32:07,860 --> 00:32:09,880
He had another kid...

584
00:32:12,940 --> 00:32:14,960
with Holly.

585
00:32:17,570 --> 00:32:20,210
Remember that photo we found up at the ranch?

586
00:32:20,220 --> 00:32:21,780
That was her.

587
00:32:22,090 --> 00:32:23,950
Her name's Rebecca.

588
00:32:23,960 --> 00:32:25,980
Dad kept her photo.

589
00:32:26,630 --> 00:32:28,260
Of course.

590
00:32:28,270 --> 00:32:30,010
And, um...

591
00:32:30,040 --> 00:32:33,320
So does, uh, does--does Mom know about this?

592
00:32:33,330 --> 00:32:36,230
No! And, Kevin, she never will, OK?

593
00:32:36,240 --> 00:32:37,410
Oh, and-- and have you met her?

594
00:32:37,420 --> 00:32:39,650
- I mean are we gonna meet her?   
- No and no.

595
00:32:39,660 --> 00:32:41,210
Well, we are talking about another sister.

596
00:32:41,220 --> 00:32:44,630
No, actually, we're not talking about her anymore ever again.

597
00:32:44,640 --> 00:32:46,300
Okay? Can we please just go home?

598
00:32:46,310 --> 00:32:49,620
- I don't think we should leave until we --
- Kev, Kev, Kev,

599
00:32:49,850 --> 00:32:51,720
just let it go, okay?

600
00:32:51,730 --> 00:32:53,280
There's a bank in town.

601
00:32:53,290 --> 00:32:55,180
We'll get cash there.

602
00:32:57,310 --> 00:33:00,290
Yeah, sure.  Yeah. Let's-- yeah, let's let it go. Of course.

603
00:33:07,240 --> 00:33:09,250
Uh, hey, Jack, if it's okay with you,

604
00:33:09,260 --> 00:33:12,240
I'd like to introduce the McCallister segment.

605
00:33:12,250 --> 00:33:13,540
Yeah, sure. It's your interview.

606
00:33:13,550 --> 00:33:15,190
- and we're on in three...    
- Thanks.

607
00:33:15,200 --> 00:33:16,450
Two...

608
00:33:16,530 --> 00:33:20,070
Welcome. Obama mulls an '08 run, election day fallout,

609
00:33:20,080 --> 00:33:23,210
and we go toe-to-toe on gay marriage, but first,

610
00:33:23,220 --> 00:33:26,410
an exclusive interview with Senator Robert McCallister,

611
00:33:26,420 --> 00:33:29,120
who sat down yesterday with our own Kitty Walker.

612
00:33:29,290 --> 00:33:31,370
- Kitty.  
- Thank you, Jack.

613
00:33:32,260 --> 00:33:34,170
In the interview that you are about to see,

614
00:33:34,180 --> 00:33:36,990
I asked Senator McCallister about his stem cell bill,

615
00:33:37,000 --> 00:33:42,290
his position on Iraq and his aspiration towards higher executive office.

616
00:33:42,880 --> 00:33:47,290
What I didn't ask him about was his recent divorce.

617
00:33:47,930 --> 00:33:50,390
Now I wish I could I say I didn't ask the senator about his divorce

618
00:33:50,400 --> 00:33:54,320
because of some high-minded notion of journalistic integrity, but...

619
00:33:55,440 --> 00:33:58,610
it was just the opposite.

620
00:33:59,200 --> 00:34:05,490
I have a brother who served in Afghanistan and was recently called back to serve in Iraq.

621
00:34:07,530 --> 00:34:10,330
And I did the senator a favor in the hope that he would do me one

622
00:34:10,340 --> 00:34:13,230
and use his influence to keep my brother home...

623
00:34:14,540 --> 00:34:20,230
to keep him from fighting in a war that I have defended on this very program.

624
00:34:20,410 --> 00:34:22,450
Senator McCallister rightly refused to help me.

625
00:34:22,460 --> 00:34:24,040
His integrity remains intact.

626
00:34:24,050 --> 00:34:28,010
But mine, however, less so.

627
00:34:28,860 --> 00:34:30,780
Mistakes were made.

628
00:34:30,980 --> 00:34:33,700
President Ronald Reagan said those words 20 years ago at a time

629
00:34:33,710 --> 00:34:37,200
when admitting a mistake was perceived as a sign of strength,

630
00:34:37,210 --> 00:34:39,080
not weakness.

631
00:34:41,780 --> 00:34:44,000
I made a mistake.

632
00:34:44,630 --> 00:34:48,480
I made a mistake in compromising the interview that you're about to see,

633
00:34:48,990 --> 00:34:54,880
and I made a mistake in continuing to defend a war that is in desperate need of reexamination,

634
00:34:55,250 --> 00:35:02,620
reexamination which cannot come until we acknowledge that the war itself was a mistake.

635
00:35:03,040 --> 00:35:06,520
None of this is meant to serve as an excuse for my own conduct,

636
00:35:06,530 --> 00:35:12,260
but I do hope that you will find in your hearts to accept my apology.

637
00:35:14,740 --> 00:35:15,530
Thank you, Kitty.

638
00:35:15,540 --> 00:35:19,970
And now our interview with Senator Robert McCallister.

639
00:35:20,490 --> 00:35:22,600
... and back in 15.

640
00:35:23,750 --> 00:35:25,340
Kitty.

641
00:35:30,470 --> 00:35:32,670
You were right to say something.

642
00:35:34,160 --> 00:35:36,080
Do you realize with gas, food and the car,

643
00:35:36,090 --> 00:35:38,420
this trip actually cost us money?

644
00:35:38,820 --> 00:35:40,950
It's just, I never remember Dad coming out here.

645
00:35:40,960 --> 00:35:43,170
Well, he must have at some point.

646
00:35:43,280 --> 00:35:44,630
What?

647
00:35:44,770 --> 00:35:46,950
- This is the only bank.   
- Yeah.

648
00:35:46,960 --> 00:35:49,480
Maybe this is where Dad got the mortgage.

649
00:35:50,270 --> 00:35:51,460
Excuse me.

650
00:35:51,470 --> 00:35:53,610
Hey, uh, my father passed away recently,

651
00:35:53,620 --> 00:35:56,610
and I think he might have had a loan through your bank. William Walker.

652
00:35:56,620 --> 00:35:58,450
Oh, uh, let me check the records.

653
00:35:58,460 --> 00:36:00,550
Look, Dad bought that land for a reason.

654
00:36:00,560 --> 00:36:02,210
I mean, he must have had a reason.

655
00:36:02,510 --> 00:36:03,900
Maybe the reason's in the loan docs.

656
00:36:03,910 --> 00:36:05,560
I agree.

657
00:36:06,100 --> 00:36:09,210
I'm sorry. There's no loans to a William Walker.

658
00:36:09,710 --> 00:36:13,150
But, uh, he did maintain a safe deposit box with us.

659
00:36:15,430 --> 00:36:18,330
Uh, I'm--I'm the executor of Mr. Walker's estate,

660
00:36:18,340 --> 00:36:20,440
and I'd like to see that box, please.

661
00:36:20,450 --> 00:36:23,510
Well, I'll need a death certificate and a copy of the will.

662
00:36:23,520 --> 00:36:25,220
Of course. What's your fax number?

663
00:36:29,460 --> 00:36:31,170
No, they're just papers.

664
00:36:34,370 --> 00:36:36,350
It's a letter for Mom.

665
00:36:38,000 --> 00:36:39,260
What's that?

666
00:36:39,270 --> 00:36:40,420
Oh, it's an easement.

667
00:36:40,430 --> 00:36:43,520
It's, uh, it's kind of a free pass to use someone else's land.

668
00:36:43,530 --> 00:36:46,680
Look, Dad gave permission to the army to drive over the land he bought.

669
00:36:50,540 --> 00:36:51,630
Oh, my God.

670
00:36:51,640 --> 00:36:54,070
Don't tell me.  Dad used to be a woman.

671
00:36:54,100 --> 00:36:56,820
No, no. There's a survivorship clause.

672
00:36:57,770 --> 00:37:00,870
Upon Dad's death, we can sell the land to the army.

673
00:37:01,040 --> 00:37:03,020
The sale price...

674
00:37:03,030 --> 00:37:05,790
of the land is, uh, is--is--is liquidated.

675
00:37:05,800 --> 00:37:07,470
It's a set amount.

676
00:37:07,480 --> 00:37:10,880
It is it enough to pay back the money Dad stole?

677
00:37:12,040 --> 00:37:14,950
Yeah, and--and-- and then some.

678
00:37:17,180 --> 00:37:19,850
William's Folly is worth...

679
00:37:20,270 --> 00:37:23,280
over $30 million.

680
00:37:26,460 --> 00:37:28,360
- No.  
- Yeah.

681
00:37:28,370 --> 00:37:30,050
- Really?  
- Yeah.

682
00:37:45,150 --> 00:37:46,280
It's your brother.

683
00:37:47,690 --> 00:37:49,070
I'm hungry.

684
00:37:50,020 --> 00:37:53,410
Uh, please warn me in advance which entrees were prepared with Kitty's loving hands.

685
00:37:53,420 --> 00:37:56,440
Uh, you guys know that I'm standing right here, right?

686
00:37:56,590 --> 00:37:58,310
- Good morning. 
- Morning.

687
00:37:58,480 --> 00:37:59,570
Wait, you're cooking?

688
00:37:59,580 --> 00:38:01,550
Under the proper supervision.

689
00:38:02,720 --> 00:38:04,820
I can see your appetite's returned.

690
00:38:04,830 --> 00:38:05,830
Kitty, phone call.

691
00:38:05,840 --> 00:38:07,950
Uh, take a message, please.

692
00:38:07,960 --> 00:38:10,130
Sure. What should I tell the senator?

693
00:38:20,650 --> 00:38:21,650
Hello?

694
00:38:21,910 --> 00:38:25,750
Happy Thanksgiving, and good interview.

695
00:38:25,760 --> 00:38:27,400
I thought it came off particularly well.

696
00:38:27,410 --> 00:38:31,600
Oh, well, that's probably because I didn't ask if you slept with the nanny.

697
00:38:31,610 --> 00:38:35,400
If that's regret that I'm sensing, then for the record, no, I didn't.

698
00:38:35,770 --> 00:38:37,960
So how fast did they fire you?

699
00:38:37,970 --> 00:38:39,980
Well, they haven't fired me yet.

700
00:38:39,990 --> 00:38:41,200
Really? That's too bad.

701
00:38:41,210 --> 00:38:43,170
I was hoping you'd be back on the market.

702
00:38:43,180 --> 00:38:44,340
Excuse me?

703
00:38:44,350 --> 00:38:47,650
I could use somebody like you on my communications staff.

704
00:38:47,660 --> 00:38:51,410
Y-you're offering me a job on your staff?

705
00:38:51,420 --> 00:38:53,220
No, as my nanny.

706
00:38:54,480 --> 00:38:56,230
You don't have to say yes right away.

707
00:38:56,240 --> 00:38:58,120
Just tell me you'll think about it.

708
00:39:01,600 --> 00:39:03,480
Yeah, I'll think about it.

709
00:39:03,710 --> 00:39:05,640
Happy Thanksgiving, Senator.

710
00:39:05,650 --> 00:39:07,360
You, too.

711
00:39:11,560 --> 00:39:12,710
That's incredible news.

712
00:39:12,720 --> 00:39:14,490
Yeah, it is incredible.

713
00:39:14,500 --> 00:39:16,150
So we're gonna be all right, then?

714
00:39:16,160 --> 00:39:17,720
You could put it that way.

715
00:39:17,730 --> 00:39:20,930
We're not going into bankruptcy, Nora. That's the main thing.

716
00:39:21,560 --> 00:39:23,000
We were looking through Dad's stuff,

717
00:39:23,010 --> 00:39:26,270
and we found this, addressed to you.

718
00:39:26,990 --> 00:39:28,740
We didn't open it.

719
00:39:30,850 --> 00:39:32,540
That's Dad's handwriting.

720
00:39:35,040 --> 00:39:36,970
I know he wasn't perfect, but...

721
00:39:37,350 --> 00:39:42,130
still, he was a lot more than what we've been giving him credit for lately.

722
00:39:42,640 --> 00:39:45,420
Yeah, he was.

723
00:40:02,630 --> 00:40:04,670
"My dearest Nora,"

724
00:40:04,680 --> 00:40:07,640
"There's a part of me that hopes you never read this."

725
00:40:07,650 --> 00:40:12,480
"Because if you are, it means that you've discovered some of the mistakes I've made in my life."

726
00:40:12,490 --> 00:40:14,730
"And while I've tried to set those mistakes right,"

727
00:40:14,740 --> 00:40:19,180
"I know that I'll never be able to completely repair your trust."

728
00:40:19,230 --> 00:40:23,080
"It tortures me to think that I've ever caused you a moment's pain."

729
00:40:23,090 --> 00:40:25,160
"But I know I have."

730
00:40:26,300 --> 00:40:29,290
"I only hope that you can find it in your heart-- "

731
00:40:29,300 --> 00:40:33,980
"a heart which is far better and purer than mine-- to forgive me my sins."

732
00:40:35,630 --> 00:40:38,750
"Because despite my mistakes and errors in judgment,"

733
00:40:38,760 --> 00:40:41,320
"I have always loved you."

734
00:40:42,220 --> 00:40:45,980
"I have always treasured your love and the love of our children."

735
00:40:45,990 --> 00:40:48,820
"Each of one of them is a little piece of you."

